200-301.

00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:12.559
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:12.559 --> 00:00:17.589
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:17.589 --> 00:00:19.060
of videos.

00:00:19.060 --> 00:00:20.060
Thanks for your help.

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:22.390
Let’s get started.

00:00:22.390 --> 00:00:27.060
In this lab we’ll configure IP addresses
on a Cisco router.

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:33.520
This is like the demo topology I used in Day
8’s main video, I just changed the IP addresses.

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:45.611
We still have one class A network, 15.0.0.0/8,
one class B network, 182.98.0.0/16, and one

00:00:45.611 --> 00:00:50.010
class C network, 201.191.20.0/24.

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:53.890
Let’s get started.

00:00:53.890 --> 00:00:56.580
The first step is to configure R1’s hostname.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:02.490
I haven’t done any configurations yet on
R1, so it still has the default hostname of

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:03.490
‘router’.

00:01:03.490 --> 00:01:08.229
Let’s go on to the CLI of R1.

00:01:08.229 --> 00:01:11.479
Now I’ll use enable to enter privileged
exec mode.

00:01:11.479 --> 00:01:18.280
Then, to configure the hostname, we have to
be in global config mode, so ‘conf t’.

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:20.950
Now let’s set the hostname.

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:22.240
Hostname R1.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:26.509
Okay, you can see the prompt changes to display
the new hostname.

00:01:26.509 --> 00:01:29.679
That’s all for step 1.

00:01:29.679 --> 00:01:35.990
Step 2 is to use a ‘show’ command to view
a list of R1’s interfaces, their IP addresses,

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:37.710
status, etc.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:39.530
Do you remember what command that is?

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:44.109
It’s a very helpful command which you’ll
use a lot as you configure Cisco routers.

00:01:44.109 --> 00:01:48.200
It’s show ip interface brief.

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:51.049
But as you can see, the command doesn’t
work.

00:01:51.049 --> 00:01:52.270
Why is that?

00:01:52.270 --> 00:01:57.649
Well, its because ‘show’ commands are
normally done from privileged exec mode.

00:01:57.649 --> 00:02:03.240
However, let me use the ‘up’ arrow to
return to the previous command, then I’ll

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:09.860
use the shortcut ‘control A’, so hold the
control key and press A, and then cursor returns

00:02:09.869 --> 00:02:11.780
to the beginning of the line.

00:02:11.780 --> 00:02:16.890
Then, type ‘do’ in front of the command,
and now it lets me enter the command from

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:19.860
global config mode.

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:24.439
Now you can see a list of interfaces,
their IP addresses, which are unset at

00:02:24.439 --> 00:02:26.850
the moment, and their statuses.

00:02:26.850 --> 00:02:32.100
Remember, the ‘status’ column indicates
the Layer 1 status.

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:37.069
Currently their status is administratively
down, because Cisco router interfaces have

00:02:37.069 --> 00:02:40.830
the ‘shutdown’ command applied to them
by default.

00:02:40.830 --> 00:02:45.510
The protocol column indicates the layer 2
status of the interface.

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:51.099
Because layer 1 is shutdown, layer 2 cant
operate, so they are all down.

00:02:51.099 --> 00:02:57.110
We will configure gigabitethernet0/0, 0/1,
and 0/2 in this lab, so they should all become

00:02:57.110 --> 00:03:00.790
UP, UP afterwards.

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:06.219
Step 3 is to configure the appropriate IP
addresses on R1’s interfaces, and enable

00:03:06.219 --> 00:03:07.579
them.

00:03:07.579 --> 00:03:11.640
We are also instructed to configure appropriate
interface descriptions.

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:16.830
Let’s start on the gigabitethernet0/0 interface.

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:20.770
Just for this first interface, I’ll type
out the whole command.

00:03:20.770 --> 00:03:23.960
Interface gigabitethernet 0/0.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:31.200
There we go, as you can see the prompt has
changed to show that I’m in interface configuration

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:32.200
mode.

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:35.060
Let’s configure the IP address.

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:38.610
Once again, I’ll use the full commands for
this first interface.

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:49.969
Ip address 15.255.255.254, now what’s the
appropriate subnet mask for a /8 prefix length?

00:03:49.969 --> 00:03:53.510
It’s 255.0.0.0.

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:55.609
Now let’s configure a description.

00:03:55.609 --> 00:04:00.370
I’ll indicate that this interface is connected
to switch 1.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:07.340
description, I'll put two hashtags, to SW1, and then again, hashtags.

00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:11.950
You can use different descriptions if you
want, this is just how I do descriptions.

00:04:11.950 --> 00:04:15.610
Finally, let’s enable the interface.

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:17.070
No shutdown.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:23.139
Immediately, I get two messages indicating
that the interface has come up.

00:04:23.139 --> 00:04:29.560
Before checking on the status of the interface,
I’ll configure the other two interfaces.

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:34.330
To switch to configuring another interface,
I don’t have to exit back to global config

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:36.090
mode first.

00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:42.340
I can just type ‘interface g0/1’, and now I’m
in interface config mode for gigabitethernet

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:43.400
0/1.

00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:48.380
Let’s set the IP address.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:53.850
IP address 182.98.255.254.

00:04:53.850 --> 00:04:59.900
The subnet mask for a /16 prefix length is
255.255.0.0.

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:01.990
And the description.

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:08.240
Description ## to SW2 ##. Let’s enable it.

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:09.760
No shut.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:13.650
Okay, now let’s go to the last interface.

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.840
Int g0/2.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:28.580
Ip address 201.191.20.254, and the subnet mask
for a /24 prefix length is 255.255.255.0.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:31.680
Next, the description.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:38.639
Description ## to SW3 ##. Finally, let’s
enable it.

00:05:38.639 --> 00:05:40.259
No shut.

00:05:40.259 --> 00:05:45.040
Okay, since we’re done with the configurations
I’ll use the command ‘end’ to go back

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:46.630
to privileged exec mode.

00:05:46.630 --> 00:05:51.479
Alternatively, I could have used the ‘exit’
command twice.

00:05:51.479 --> 00:05:55.430
Once to return to global config mode, and
then a second time to return to privileged

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:57.900
exec mode.

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:00.810
Now let’s check on the status of the interfaces.

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:03.740
Show ip interface brief.

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:10.520
Now you can see the IP addresses we configured,
the method lists ‘manual’ instead of unset,

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:15.169
and the layer 1 and layer 2 statuses of the
interfaces are up and up.

00:06:15.169 --> 00:06:20.530
Now, step 5 says to view the running config
to confirm the changes, and then save the

00:06:20.530 --> 00:06:21.910
config.

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:25.039
Show running-config.

00:06:25.039 --> 00:06:27.190
Here are the interfaces.

00:06:27.190 --> 00:06:31.770
You can see the descriptions, and ip addresses
we configured.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:35.770
Notice the default duplex auto and speed auto
commands.

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:41.490
Also, if you look at the vlan1 interface,
you can see the shutdown command, which as

00:06:41.490 --> 00:06:44.780
I said is applied by default to cisco router
interfaces.

00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:47.750
Okay, let’s save the config.

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:52.800
I mentioned in a previous video that there
are a few ways to save the config.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:55.259
Copy running-config startup-config.

00:06:55.259 --> 00:06:56.370
Write memory.

00:06:56.370 --> 00:06:58.080
Or, just write.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:05.289
I like to use the shortcut version of write,
W R. There we go.

00:07:05.289 --> 00:07:10.540
Step 6 is to configure the IP addresses of
PC1, PC2, and PC3.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:18.300
I’ll go on PC1 first.  To configure the
IP address, click config up here.

00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:21.449
First, notice that I pre-configured the gateway
here.

00:07:21.449 --> 00:07:25.889
I’ll talk about what the purpose of the
gateway is when we talk more about routing,

00:07:25.889 --> 00:07:29.400
but notice that its R1’s IP address.

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:36.289
Now, to configure the PC's IP address, click
on fastethernet0 here, that is PC1’s network

00:07:36.289 --> 00:07:38.389
interface card.

00:07:38.389 --> 00:07:42.400
And then here you can configure the IP address.

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:43.790
15.0.0.1.

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:45.909
And look at the subnet mask.

00:07:45.909 --> 00:07:52.319
It automatically fills in 255.0.0.0,
since this is a class A address.

00:07:52.319 --> 00:07:54.740
Okay, now we can exit out of here.

00:07:54.740 --> 00:07:58.080
Let’s do the same on PC2.

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:59.879
Click on PC2.

00:07:59.879 --> 00:08:01.580
Click config.

00:08:01.580 --> 00:08:04.319
Click on fastethernet0.

00:08:04.319 --> 00:08:12.810
The IP address is 182.98.0.1, and once again
it automatically fills in the subnet mask,

00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:19.770
this time 255.255.0.0 because this is a class
B address.

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:22.030
Now let’s go on PC3.

00:08:22.030 --> 00:08:24.139
Click on PC3.

00:08:24.139 --> 00:08:25.599
Click config.

00:08:25.599 --> 00:08:27.060
Fastethernet0.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:33.289
IP address of 201.191.20.1.

00:08:33.289 --> 00:08:40.349
And this time the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0,
for this class C address.

00:08:40.349 --> 00:08:49.900
Okay, finally let’s go back to PC1 and try
to ping.  Click desktop, then command prompt.

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:52.680
Now I’ll try to ping PC2.

00:08:52.680 --> 00:09:03.000
Ping 182.98.0.1.

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:07.020
Okay, looks like PC1 can reach PC2.

00:09:07.030 --> 00:09:09.160
How about PC3?

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:18.300
Ping 201.191.20.1.

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:23.120
Great, PC1 can ping PC3 as well.

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:28.540
So, in this lab we looked at how to configure
IP addresses on router interfaces, how to

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:34.180
configure interface descriptions, and how
to enable interfaces with the ‘no shutdown’

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:35.180
command.

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:40.450
We also configured IP addresses on PCs in
packet tracer and confirmed reachability with

00:09:40.450 --> 00:09:41.450
ping.

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:44.200
That’s all for this lab.

00:09:44.200 --> 00:09:45.790
Thank you for watching.

